              <h2>How this portion size calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This portion size calculator combines public health serving
                guidelines with practical “hand-size” estimates to give you
                realistic amounts of food per person. It is designed for:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Everyday meals (breakfast, lunch, dinner)</li>
                <li>Snacks and light bites</li>
                <li>Meal prep and batch cooking</li>
                <li>Cooking for a crowd, parties, and buffets</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Food groups we estimate</h3>
              <p>For each scenario, the tool estimates:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Protein foods</strong> – meat, fish, eggs, tofu,
                  beans, lentils
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Starchy carbs</strong> – rice, pasta, potatoes, bread,
                  grains
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Vegetables & salad</strong> – non‑starchy veg, leafy
                  greens
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Fruit</strong> – fresh, canned (in juice), or frozen
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Fats & dressings</strong> – oils, butter, spreads,
                  sauces
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Base portion sizes (per adult, moderate activity)</h3>
              <p>These are typical starting points for a balanced main meal:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <ul class="list-disc pl-5">
                  <li>
                    <strong>Protein:</strong> 100–150 g cooked (≈ 3.5–5.3 oz) →
                    we use 120 g
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Starchy carbs:</strong> 120–180 g cooked (≈ 4.2–6.3
                    oz) → we use 150 g
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Vegetables:</strong> 150–250 g (≈ 5.3–8.8 oz) → we
                    use 200 g
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Fruit (if included):</strong> 80–120 g → we use 100
                    g
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Added fats:</strong> 10–15 g (≈ 2–3 tsp oil) → we
                    use 12 g
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>
                Breakfast and snacks use smaller fractions of these base
                amounts, while party/buffet settings add a buffer to account for
                people taking slightly more and sampling multiple dishes.
              </p>

              <h3>Adjustments for age, activity, and goal</h3>
              <p>The calculator applies multipliers to the base portions:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Age group:</strong> toddlers &lt; children &lt;
                  teens/adults; seniors slightly lower overall but with protein
                  preserved.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Activity level:</strong> active people get larger carb
                  and overall portions; sedentary people get slightly smaller.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Goal:</strong> for weight loss, energy‑dense foods
                  (carbs & fats) are reduced and vegetables increased; for
                  weight gain, the opposite.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Hand-size portion guide</h2>
              <p>
                To make portions easier to visualize without a scale or
                measuring cups, the table also shows a hand‑based estimate:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Protein:</strong> 1 palm = ~90–100 g cooked meat/fish
                  or firm tofu
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Carbs:</strong> 1 cupped hand = ~40–50 g cooked
                  rice/pasta or 1 small potato
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Vegetables:</strong> 1 fist = ~80–100 g raw veg or
                  salad
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Fruit:</strong> 1 fist = 1 medium fruit or ~80–100 g
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Fats:</strong> 1 thumb = ~7–8 g (≈ 1 tbsp oil or nut
                  butter)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator converts the gram/ounce estimate into an
                approximate number of palms, fists, or thumbs per person.
              </p>

              <h2>Using the calculator for different scenarios</h2>

              <h3>1. Everyday family meals</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Select <strong>Main meal</strong> and the number of people.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Choose <strong>Adult</strong> or <strong>Child</strong> as
                  needed, and the typical activity level.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Set the goal to <strong>Weight maintenance</strong> for most
                  families.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>Calculate portions</strong> to see how much
                  protein, carbs, and vegetables to cook.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>Example: 2 adults + 2 children, main meal, maintenance:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Protein: around 400–450 g total</li>
                <li>Starchy carbs: around 450–500 g cooked</li>
                <li>Vegetables: around 700–800 g total</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Weight loss</h3>
              <p>For weight loss, the calculator:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Reduces starchy carbs and added fats by ~20–25%</li>
                <li>
                  Keeps protein similar or slightly higher (to preserve muscle)
                </li>
                <li>Increases vegetables to help you feel full</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This is a practical starting point, but if you have medical
                conditions, always follow advice from your doctor or dietitian.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Meal prep and batch cooking</h3>
              <p>To plan a week of lunches or dinners:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>Set <strong>Number of people</strong> to 1.</li>
                <li>
                  Multiply the number of meals you want (e.g., 10 meals) and
                  enter that as “Number of people”.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use the totals column to see how much food to buy and cook.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>4. Parties and buffets</h3>
              <p>
                Party portions are different from plated meals. People graze,
                some eat more, some less. The
                <strong>Party / buffet</strong> option:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Reduces protein per person slightly (people often eat less
                  meat at buffets)
                </li>
                <li>Increases carbs and snack‑type foods</li>
                <li>Adds a 20–30% buffer to reduce the risk of running out</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and safety notes</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This calculator provides <strong>general estimates</strong>,
                  not medical advice.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Individual needs vary with health conditions, medications,
                  pregnancy, and breastfeeding.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Children, older adults, and people with specific medical
                  conditions may need tailored guidance.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For therapeutic diets (e.g., diabetes, kidney disease, coeliac
                  disease), consult a registered dietitian.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>Is this portion size calculator suitable for children?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, there are separate settings for toddlers and children.
                Portions are scaled down compared with adults, but still assume
                a generally healthy child without specific medical needs. For
                under‑2s or fussy eaters, use the results as a loose guide and
                follow your pediatrician’s advice.
              </p>

              <h3>How do I use this with food labels and serving sizes?</h3>
              <p>
                Food labels list a “serving size” and nutrients per serving. Our
                calculator gives a <strong>portion size</strong> in
                grams/ounces. You can divide your portion by the label serving
                size to see how many label servings you are eating, then
                multiply the calories and nutrients accordingly.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I switch between grams and cups?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Use the <strong>Units</strong> dropdown to switch between
                metric (grams, milliliters) and US/Imperial (ounces, cups). The
                underlying amounts are the same; only the display changes. For
                best accuracy, grams are preferred because “cups” can vary with
                food type.
              </p>

              <h3>
                How does this compare to official guidelines like MyPlate?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Official tools such as MyPlate or national dietary guidelines
                focus on daily servings across all meals. This calculator
                focuses on <strong>per‑meal portions</strong> and practical
                cooking amounts. The underlying ranges are broadly consistent
                with those guidelines but presented in a more kitchen‑friendly
                way.
              </p>
            </section>
